  "report": {
    "narrative": [
      "The preview data does not include job-level metadata (job IDs, users/accounts/QOS, job-to-node placement, or node->partition mapping), so direct correlation from “hot/problematic nodes” to specific partitions/users/jobs cannot be established with strong evidence.\n\nWhat can be connected with available evidence:\n- Node-side stress signal present: GPU temperature hotspots are concentrated on k002-004-v* (card0) and, to a lesser extent, k002-003 (cards 2/4/6). These are the only node-identified “stressed” resources in the preview.\n- Scheduler-side demand signal present: pending jobs are heavily concentrated in partitions mi3001x (36) and mi2104x (26), with all other partitions at 1–2 pending. This indicates that user demand (workload pressure) is primarily targeting those GPU families/partitions.\n\nLikely workload cause (inference, low confidence): the thermal hotspots could be driven by high utilization workloads (training/inference) running on whichever partitions those nodes belong to; however, without Slurm allocation/job placement metrics, it’s equally plausible that the hot nodes are unrelated to the most-backlogged partitions (e.g., they might be fully utilized in a different partition with little queue).\n\nSummary of association:\n- Partitions most associated with scheduler pressure: mi3001x and mi2104x (strong evidence via pending metrics).\n- Users most associated with stress: not determinable from preview (no user/account labels).\n- Hot nodes associated with workload context: not determinable from preview (no job-to-node correlation)."
    ],
    "highlights": [
      "Hot resources (node-identified): k002-004-v5/v7/v1/v8/v6 (GPU card0) and k002-003 (GPU cards 4/2/6) show the highest temperatures in the window.",
      "Workload pressure (scheduler-identified): pending jobs are concentrated in mi3001x=36 and mi2104x=26; other partitions are ≤2 pending at the snapshot.",
      "Correlation gap: no job IDs, users/accounts, or node<->partition/job placement metadata in the preview, so attributing hot nodes to specific partitions/users is ambiguous.",
      "Operational takeaway: treat partition backlogs (mi3001x, mi2104x) as the best-supported capacity signal; treat hot nodes as independent investigation targets until job placement data is available."
    ],
